{
  "doc_id": "59395",
  "text": "A large share of general practitioner (GP) and specialist visits can be attributed to a small proportion of health insured individuals [CITATION_1] . For example, it has been shown that the most frequent 1% of attenders accounted for 6% of all GP consultations (Leeds, four general practices; 44,146 patients and 470,712 consultations; year 1991 to 1995) [CITATION_2] . Consequently, these so-called frequent attenders place a tremendous burden on the health care system [CITATION_3] , underpinning the significance of characterizing this group in detail. A recent systematic review identified some studies investigating the correlates of frequent attendance in late life [CITATION_4] . Frequent attenders in late life, for example, were older and had more physical illnesses compared to non-frequent attenders [CITATION_5] . Indeed, the association between physical illnesses and frequent attendance was found in six out of ten reviewed studies at the primary care level [CITATION_6] .",
